“A God-given conscience will not let us rest until our duty is done.”  – Robert L. Simpson, CR
“I desire so to conduct the affairs of this administration that if at the end I have lost every other friend on earth, I shall at least have one friend left, and that friend shall be down inside of me.”  – Abraham Lincoln, CR
“The most important human endeavor is the striving for morality in our actions. Our inner balance and even our very existence depend on it. Only morality in our actions can give beauty and dignity to life.”  – Albert Einstein, CR
“Physical courage, which despises all danger, will make a man brave in one way; and moral courage, which despises all opinion, will make a man brave in another.”  – Charles Caleb Colton, CR
“Never 'for the sake of peace and quiet' deny your own experience or convictions.”  – Dag Hammarskjold, CR
“The awful thing is that beauty is mysterious as well as terrible. God and the devil are fighting there and the battlefield is the heart of man.”  – Fyodor Dostoyevsky, The Brothers Karamazov
“Labor to keep alive in your breast that little celestial fire, called conscience.”  – George Washington, The Brothers Karamazov
“A man of integrity will never listen to any plea against conscience.”  – Henry Home, The Brothers Karamazov
“Cowardice asks the question, 'Is it safe?' Expediency asks the question, 'Is it polite?' Vanity asks the question, 'Is it popular?' But conscience asks the question, 'Is it right?' And there comes a point when one must take a position that is neither safe, nor polite, nor popular, but he must take it because his conscience tells him that it is right.”  – Martin Luther King, Jr., The Brothers Karamazov
“It is difficult to make a man miserable while he feels he is worthy of himself and claims kindred to the great God who made him.”  – Abraham Lincoln, The Brothers Karamazov
“Never do anything against conscience even if the state demands it.”  – Albert Einstein, The Brothers Karamazov
“He who sacrifices his conscience to ambition burns a picture to obtain the ashes.”  – Chinese Proverb, The Brothers Karamazov
“Whatever is done without ostentation, and without the people being witnesses of it, is, in my opinion, most praiseworthy: not that the public eye should be entirely avoided, for good actions desire to be placed in the light; but notwithstanding this, the greatest theater for virtue is conscience.”  – Marcus Tullius Cicero, The Brothers Karamazov
“The superior man understands what is right; the inferior man understands what will sell.”  – Confucius, The Brothers Karamazov
“The more faithfully you listen to the voices within you, the better you will hear what is sounding outside.”  – Dag Hammarskjold, The Brothers Karamazov
“If we have not peace within ourselves, it is in vain to seek it from outward sources.”  – Francois de la Rochefoucauld, The Brothers Karamazov
“Only in quiet waters things mirror themselves undistorted. Only in a quiet mind is adequate perception of the world.”  – Hans Margolius, The Brothers Karamazov
“Two things fill me with constantly increasing admiration and awe, the longer and more earnestly I reflect on them: the starry heavens without and the moral law within.”  – Immanuel Kant, The Brothers Karamazov
“In matters of conscience, the law of majority has no place.”  – Mahatma Gandhi, The Brothers Karamazov
“Two men please God -- who serves Him with all his heart because he knows him; who seeks Him with all his heart because he knows Him not.”  – Nikita Ivanovich Panin, The Brothers Karamazov
“In matters of conscience, first thoughts are best; in matters of prudence, last thoughts.”  – Robert Hall, The Brothers Karamazov
“Conscience is thoroughly well-bred and soon leaves off talking to those who do not wish to hear it.”  – Samuel Butler, The Brothers Karamazov
“Let us satisfy our own consciences, and trouble not ourselves by looking for fame... The praise bad actions obtain dies soon away; if good deeds are at first unworthily received, they are afterward more properly appreciated.”  – Seneca, The Brothers Karamazov
“Conscience warns us as a friend before it punishes as a judge.”  – Stanislaus Leszczynski, The Brothers Karamazov
“The accumulation of right choices builds inner spiritual strength and divine character.”  – Rulon G. Craven, General Conference
“The great secret of success is to go through life as a man who never gets used up...A man can do only what a man can do. But if he does that each day he can sleep at night and do it again the next day.”  – Albert Schweitzer, General Conference
“Courage to start and willingness to keep everlasting at it are the requisites for success.”  – Alonzo Newton Benn, General Conference
“Excellence is an art won by training and habituation. We do not act rightly because we have virtue or excellence, but we rather have those because we have acted rightly. We are what we repeatedly do. Excellence, then, is not an act but a habit.”  – Aristotle, General Conference
“Excellence is an art won by training and habituation.”  – Aristotle, General Conference
“Enough shovels of earth - a mountain. Enough pails of water - a river.”  – Chinese Proverb, General Conference
“The person who removes a mountain begins by carrying away small stones.”  – Chinese Proverb, General Conference
“It seems, in fact, as though the second half of a man's life is made up of nothing but the habits he has accumulated during the first half.”  – Fyodor Dostoyevsky, General Conference
“The heights by great men reached and kept, Were not attained by sudden flight, But they, while their companions slept, Were toiling upward in the night.”  – Henry Wadsworth Longfellow, General Conference
“The seed you sow today will not produce crop till tomorrow. For this reason, your identity does not lie in your current results. This is not who you are. Your current results are who you were.”  – James A. Ray, General Conference
“You don't have to change that much for it to make a great deal of difference. A few simple disciplines can have a major impact on how your life works out in the next 90 days, let alone in the next 12 months or the next 3 years.”  – Jim Rohn, General Conference
“Motivation is what gets you started. Habit is what keeps you going.”  – Jim Ryun, General Conference
“How you respond to the challenge in the second half will determine what you become after the game, whether you are a winner or a loser.”  – Lou Holtz, General Conference
“The victory of success is half won when one gains the habit of setting goals and achieving them. Even the most tedious chore will become endurable as you parade through each day convinced that every task, no matter how menial or boring, brings you closer to fulfilling your dreams”  – Og Mandino, General Conference
“Creating success is tough. But keeping it is tougher. You have to keep producing, you can never stop.”  – Pete Rose, General Conference
“All great masters are chiefly distinguished by the power of adding a second, a third, and perhaps a fourth step in a continuous line. Many a man had taken the first step. With every additional step you enhance immensely the value of your first.”  – Ralph Waldo Emerson, General Conference
“The power of a man increases steadily by continuing in one direction.”  – Ralph Waldo Emerson, General Conference
“Success seems to be largely a matter of hanging on after others have let go.”  – William Feather, General Conference
“The secret of success is constancy of purpose.”  – Benjamin Disraeli, General Conference
“Diligence is the mother of good luck.”  – Benjamin Franklin, General Conference
“The strength of a man's virtue is measured by his habitual acts.”  – Blaise Pascal, General Conference
“The superior man is firm in the right way, and not merely firm.”  – Confucius, General Conference
“Consistency is the foundation of virtue.”  – Francis Bacon, General Conference
“Habits are to the soul what the veins and arteries are to the blood, the courses in which it moves.”  – Horace Bushnell, General Conference
“If I miss one day of practice, I notice it. If I miss two days, the critics notice it. If I miss three days, the audience notices it.”  – Ignace Paderewski, General Conference
“Success is nothing more than a few simple disciplines, practiced every day; while failure is simply a few errors in judgment, repeated every day. It is the accumulative weight of our disciplines and our judgments that leads us to either fortune or failure.”  – Jim Rohn, General Conference
